<div class="thumbcaption">
<div class="magnify"><a href="/wiki/File:Gradient_vectors_on_cos(x)*cos(y).png" class="internal" title="Enlarge"><img src="/skins-1.5/common/images/magnify-clip.png" width="15" height="11" alt="" /></a></div>
Gradient on 3D surface - red is quicker, blue slower growth. On the top there are both growth and gradient zero.</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>In <a href="/wiki/Vector_calculus" title="Vector calculus">vector calculus</a>, the <b>gradient</b> of a <a href="/wiki/Scalar_field" title="Scalar field">scalar field</a> is a <a href="/wiki/Vector_field" title="Vector field">vector field</a> which points in the direction of the greatest rate of increase of the scalar field, and whose <a href="/wiki/Magnitude_(mathematics)" title="Magnitude (mathematics)">magnitude</a> is the greatest rate of change.</p>
<p>A generalization of the gradient for functions on a <a href="/wiki/Euclidean_space" title="Euclidean space">Euclidean space</a> which have values in another Euclidean space is the <a href="/wiki/Jacobian" title="Jacobian">Jacobian</a>. A further generalization for a function from one <a href="/wiki/Banach_space" title="Banach space">Banach space</a> to another is the <a href="/wiki/Fr%C3%A9chet_derivative" title="Fréchet derivative">Fréchet derivative</a>.</p>
